## 5. Exact Git Command Flow (with placeholders)

From your project folder `java-copilot-demo`:

```bash
# 1. Initialize Git repo
git init

# 2. Create and edit .gitignore (then:)
git add .gitignore
git commit -m "Add .gitignore for Java and VS Code"

# 3. Add all current files (Main.java, etc.)
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit: setup Java project with Main class"

# 4. Create GitHub repo (in browser), then connect it:
git remote add origin https://github.com/<YOUR_GITHUB_USERNAME>/java-copilot-demo.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

# 5. Make a change (e.g., add Javadoc), then:
git add Main.java
git commit -m "Add factorial and sum methods with Javadoc"
git push

# 6. Create a feature branch, change code, commit, merge
git checkout -b feature/more-output
# (edit Main.java)
git add Main.java
git commit -m "Add extra console output to main"
git checkout main
git merge feature/more-output
git push

# 7. Introduce a bug & recover from history
# Make bad change in Main.java, then:
git add Main.java
git commit -m "Introduce bug in factorial for demo"
git push

# Show history
git log --oneline

# Suppose GOOD commit before bug is abc1234:
git checkout abc1234 src/Main.java
git commit -am "Restore factorial implementation from previous commit"
git push
